HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 874
By Vital
A RESOLUTION to celebrate the eightieth anniversary of the
Tennessee Wildlife Federation.
WHEREAS, the Tennessee Wildlife Federation is a nonprofit organization founded on
February 12th, 1946, as the Tennessee Conservation League at Chattanooga's Read House
Hotel by outdoor writers, sportsmen, and community leaders in response to dwindling wildlife
populations and the widespread decline of Tennessee's natural resources; and,
WHEREAS, for eighty years, the Tennessee Wildlife Federation has been dedicated to
conserving Tennessee's fish and wildlife, protecting access to our outdoor spaces, and
promoting Tennesseans' hunting and fishing heritage; and
WHEREAS, the Tennessee Wildlife Federation has been instrumental in bringing
healthy deer, turkey, elk, and other game and non-game species' populations back to
Tennessee through policy efforts, active wildlife management, and habitat conservation
projects; and
WHEREAS, over the past eight decades, the Tennessee Wildlife Federation has evolved
from a grassroots conservation organization into a trusted statewide voice on wildlife
management, outdoor recreation, and conservation policy, working alongside hunters, anglers,
landowners, scientists, and policymakers to advance practical, science-based solutions that
benefit all Tennesseans; and
WHEREAS, healthy habitats and wildlife populations require robust, common-sense
policies supporting conservation and active, science-backed management, and the Tennessee
Wildlife Federation is a leader in promoting sound conservation policy; and
WHEREAS, the Tennessee Wildlife Federation gives back to the State of Tennessee
through outdoor outreach programs, including Hunters for the Hungry, which provides hunger
HJR0874
012771
- 1 -

relief organizations with no-cost venison donated by deer hunters, allowing hunters to do what
they love, donate venison, and give back to their communities; and
WHEREAS, the Tennessee Wildlife Federation's Scholastic Clay Target Program
provides Tennessee's youth with the opportunity to participate in trap, skeet, and sporting clays
with their peers across the State, teaching the importance of safe firearm handling,
responsibility, leadership, and teamwork while promoting healthy competition; and
WHEREAS, the Tennessee Wildlife Federation's Hunting and Fishing Academy recruits
the next generation of hunters, anglers, and conservationists of all ages and has allowed
Tennesseans to engage with nature while supporting conservation efforts; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and congratulate the Tennessee Wildlife Federation for eighty
years of conservation leadership and dedication to conservation efforts across the Volunteer
State.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
